snippet.textDisplay:
I've never shared a video twice on my timeline. Today I am doing it  because A) It's been a long time since I gave my opinion about a musical performance, B) I can't express how much Atif nailed this evergreen Qawwali. And when I was just complaining about how the South Asian industry abandoned creating magical Qawwalis like this one, that Coke Studio answered my inner wish by producing this humble tribute to the legends Sabri Bros. It is true that this attempt received quite a lot of criticism highlighting Atif's inability to do justice to the original version but what the majority fail to understand is that this is NOT an attempt to copy Sabri Bros, I mean who does even have the guts to do so? This is just a little tribute and a very well done one. I wish my non-Urdu speaking friends could understand the meaning of each word pronounced in this Qawwali. Urdu, Persian and Arabic, three of the most poetic languages combined within one single poem about our beloved Prophet Mohammed (PBUH) . How could anything else be more perfect than that? Please enable the subtitles before watching the video to enjoy the magical effect produced by each and every word pinned by its lyricist.

Sorry for the long praise. But you have no idea how it feels like to feed a Qawwali-obsessed girl like me with performances like this one.
 
Salma,
Morocco.
